    <section id="shared-origins">
      <h2>Shared Chinese Origins</h2>
      <p>The New Year celebrations observed across East and Central Asia trace their origins to <strong>Chinese civilisation</strong>. The lunisolar calendar system developed during the Shang Dynasty (c. 1600–1046 BCE) established the astronomical framework, while the ritual traditions of winter-end sacrifices and spring welcoming ceremonies provided the cultural template. As Chinese cultural influence radiated outward through trade, migration, tributary relationships, and the spread of Buddhism, neighbouring peoples adapted these practices to their own contexts.</p>
      <p>The core elements shared by nearly all Asian New Year traditions include:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Ancestor veneration</strong> — honouring deceased family members with offerings and prayers</li>
        <li><strong>Family reunion meals</strong> — the most important meal of the year, bringing all generations together</li>
        <li><strong>The twelve-animal zodiac cycle</strong> — marking each year with an animal sign</li>
        <li><strong>Symbolic foods</strong> — specific dishes eaten for prosperity, longevity, and good fortune</li>
        <li><strong>Gift-giving to children</strong> — monetary gifts symbolising blessings for the new year</li>
        <li><strong>House cleaning and decoration</strong> — sweeping away the old year's misfortune</li>
        <li><strong>Firecrackers or noisemaking</strong> — driving away evil spirits</li>
      </ul>
      <p>What makes each tradition distinctive is how these shared elements have been transformed by local history, climate, religion, and aesthetics over centuries of independent development.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="chinese-new-year">
      <h2>Chinese Spring Festival (<span class="chinese-char">春節</span>)</h2>
      <p>The <a href="/spring-festival/">Spring Festival</a> (Chūnjié) is the mother celebration from which all others descend. Its documented history spans over three thousand years, from Shang Dynasty oracle bone inscriptions recording winter sacrifices to the elaborate fifteen-day festival codified during the Han Dynasty (206 BCE–220 CE).</p>
      <p>Key traditions include pasting red spring couplets (<span class="chinese-char">春聯</span>) on doorframes, setting off firecrackers to drive away the Nian beast, preparing a lavish reunion dinner (<span class="chinese-char">年夜飯</span>) on New Year's Eve, distributing red envelopes (<span class="chinese-char">紅包</span>) to children, and visiting temples and relatives during the first days of the new year.</p>
      <p>The festival culminates on the fifteenth day with the Lantern Festival (<span class="chinese-char">元宵節</span>), featuring lantern displays, riddle games, and tangyuan (glutinous rice balls). The entire period is governed by specific customs for each day — from welcoming the God of Wealth on the fifth day to the Jade Emperor's birthday on the ninth.</p>
      <p>For a comprehensive account of Spring Festival history and customs, see our <a href="/spring-festival/">dedicated article</a>.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="vietnamese-tet">
      <h2>Vietnamese Tết Nguyên Đán (<span class="chinese-char">節元旦</span>)</h2>
      <p><strong>Tết</strong>, short for Tết Nguyên Đán ("Festival of the First Morning"), is Vietnam's most important holiday. It falls on the same date as Chinese New Year in most years, following a calendar system adopted during the thousand-year period of Chinese rule (111 BCE–938 CE). Despite Vietnam's subsequent independence, the lunisolar calendar and many New Year customs were retained and adapted.</p>

      <h3>Linguistic Evidence of Chinese Origin</h3>
      <div class="historical-note">
        <p><strong>The vocabulary of Tết is 100% Sino-Vietnamese.</strong> Every key term comes directly from Chinese, adapted through the Sino-Vietnamese (Hán-Việt) reading system:</p>
      </div>
      <table class="elements-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Vietnamese</th><th>Chinese</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Tết</strong> (tiết)</td><td><span class="chinese-char">節</span> (<span class="pinyin">jié</span>)</td><td>Festival / season</td><td>Sino-Vietnamese reading of 節</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Nguyên Đán</strong></td><td><span class="chinese-char">元旦</span> (<span class="pinyin">yuándàn</span>)</td><td>First morning</td><td>Exact calque of the Chinese term</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Lì xì</strong></td><td><span class="chinese-char">利是</span> (<span class="pinyin">lìshì</span>)</td><td>Lucky money / red envelope</td><td>Preserves Cantonese-era pronunciation</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Câu đối</strong></td><td><span class="chinese-char">對聯</span> (<span class="pinyin">duìlián</span>)</td><td>Couplets</td><td>Sino-Vietnamese compound</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Đèn lồng</strong></td><td><span class="chinese-char">燈籠</span> (<span class="pinyin">dēnglóng</span>)</td><td>Lantern</td><td>Sino-Vietnamese compound</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Pháo</strong></td><td><span class="chinese-char">炮</span> (<span class="pinyin">pào</span>)</td><td>Firecrackers</td><td>Sino-Vietnamese reading</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Ông Táo</strong></td><td><span class="chinese-char">灶</span> (<span class="pinyin">zào</span>)</td><td>Kitchen God (Stove Lord)</td><td>Táo = Sino-Vietnamese for 灶</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <div class="pullquote">
        If Vietnamese had an independent, pre-Chinese new year celebration, we would expect native (non-Sinitic) vocabulary for its core concepts — as Thai Songkran and Khmer Chol Chnam Thmey have entirely native names and terminology. The complete absence of native Vietnamese vocabulary for Tết customs is itself evidence that the celebration was imported from Chinese culture.
      </div>

      <h3>Distinctive Traditions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Ông Táo (Kitchen God)</strong> — On the 23rd day of the twelfth lunar month, Vietnamese families release live carp into rivers, providing the Kitchen God transportation to heaven to report on the household. This parallels the Chinese Zaojun tradition but uniquely uses live fish.</li>
        <li><strong>Cây nêu (New Year pole)</strong> — A bamboo pole decorated with red cloth, clay figures, and small bells is erected in the yard to ward off evil spirits — a tradition with ancient Austroasiatic roots.</li>
        <li><strong>Bánh chưng and bánh tét</strong> — Square (northern) and cylindrical (southern) sticky rice cakes filled with mung bean and pork, wrapped in banana leaves. The Hùng Vương legend ties bánh chưng to the founding of Vietnamese civilisation.</li>
        <li><strong>Hoa mai and hoa đào</strong> — Yellow apricot blossoms (south) and pink peach blossoms (north) serve as the Vietnamese equivalents of Chinese plum blossoms, decorating every home.</li>
        <li><strong>Xông đất (First Footer)</strong> — The first person to enter the home after midnight is believed to determine the household's fortune for the entire year. Families carefully select auspicious first visitors.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>The Cat Zodiac</h3>
      <p>Vietnam's most notable divergence from the Chinese zodiac is the substitution of the <strong>Cat</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">Mão</span>) for the Rabbit. Several theories explain this: the Vietnamese word for "rabbit" (mão) sounds like "cat," or the cat was more familiar in Vietnamese agricultural life. This means 2023 was a Year of the Cat in Vietnam while it was a Year of the Rabbit in China.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="korean-seollal">
      <h2>Korean Seollal (<span class="chinese-char">설날</span>)</h2>
      <p><strong>Seollal</strong> (설날) is Korea's most significant traditional holiday, typically falling on the same day as Chinese New Year. Korean New Year customs arrived through centuries of cultural exchange with China, particularly during the Three Kingdoms period (57 BCE–668 CE) and subsequent Goryeo and Joseon dynasties. However, Korea has developed a distinctly Korean character to these celebrations.</p>

      <h3>Distinctive Traditions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Sebae (세배)</strong> — The formal deep bow (keunjeol) performed to elders is the centrepiece of Seollal. Children dress in hanbok and perform sebae to parents, grandparents, and elder relatives, receiving sebaetdon (세뱃돈, New Year money) and words of blessing in return.</li>
        <li><strong>Tteokguk (떡국)</strong> — Rice cake soup is the essential Seollal food. Eating it symbolises gaining one year of age, and Koreans traditionally say "you must eat tteokguk to become a year older." The white, coin-shaped rice cakes represent purity and prosperity.</li>
        <li><strong>Yunnori (윷놀이)</strong> — A traditional board game played with four wooden sticks, unique to Korea. Families and neighbours compete in teams, making it the most popular Seollal entertainment.</li>
        <li><strong>Charye (차례)</strong> — Ancestral rites performed on Seollal morning, with elaborate food offerings arranged on a table according to strict positional rules. This Confucian ritual is more formally structured than Chinese ancestor worship practices.</li>
        <li><strong>Bokjumeoni (복주머니)</strong> — Embroidered silk fortune pouches, traditionally filled with grain or small items, given as gifts symbolising contained blessings for the new year.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>The Korean Zodiac</h3>
      <p>Korea uses the same twelve animals as China, with identical associations to the Earthly Branches. Korean zodiac terminology uses Sino-Korean readings: 자 (ja/Rat), 축 (chuk/Ox), 인 (in/Tiger), 묘 (myo/Rabbit), 진 (jin/Dragon), 사 (sa/Snake), 오 (o/Horse), 미 (mi/Goat), 신 (sin/Monkey), 유 (yu/Rooster), 술 (sul/Dog), 해 (hae/Pig).</p>
    </section>

    <section id="japanese-shogatsu">
      <h2>Japanese Shōgatsu (<span class="chinese-char">正月</span>)</h2>
      <p><strong>Shōgatsu</strong> (正月) was historically celebrated on the lunisolar New Year, the same date as Chinese New Year. Japan adopted the Chinese calendar during the Asuka period (538–710 CE) along with Buddhism, Confucianism, and the writing system. However, during the Meiji Restoration in <strong>1873</strong>, Japan switched to the Gregorian calendar, moving New Year's Day to January 1st — making it the only major Asian civilisation to sever the connection between New Year and the lunisolar calendar.</p>

      <h3>Distinctive Traditions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Osechi-ryōri (おせち料理)</strong> — Elaborate multi-layered lacquer boxes (jūbako) filled with symbolic foods: black beans (mame, for health), herring roe (kazunoko, for fertility), shrimp (ebi, for longevity), and dozens of other dishes. Each item carries specific meaning.</li>
        <li><strong>Kadomatsu (門松)</strong> — Paired pine and bamboo decorations placed at entrances to welcome the toshigami (year deity). The arrangement's asymmetry follows traditional Japanese aesthetics.</li>
        <li><strong>Hatsumode (初詣)</strong> — The first shrine or temple visit of the new year, often undertaken at midnight or on January 1st. Major shrines like Meiji Jingū in Tokyo receive millions of visitors.</li>
        <li><strong>Otoshidama (お年玉)</strong> — Monetary gifts to children in special decorated envelopes (pochibukuro), equivalent to Chinese red envelopes but typically using white envelopes with playful designs.</li>
        <li><strong>Joya no Kane (除夜の鐘)</strong> — Temple bells rung 108 times at midnight on New Year's Eve, corresponding to the 108 worldly desires (bonnō) in Buddhist teaching.</li>
        <li><strong>Nengajō (年賀状)</strong> — New Year postcards sent in enormous quantities (billions annually at peak), featuring the zodiac animal of the incoming year. This tradition has no parallel in other Asian New Year celebrations.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>The Japanese Zodiac</h3>
      <p>Japan uses the same twelve animals (jūnishi, 十二支) with Japanese readings: ne (子/Rat), ushi (丑/Ox), tora (寅/Tiger), u (卯/Rabbit), tatsu (辰/Dragon), mi (巳/Snake), uma (午/Horse), hitsuji (未/Goat), saru (申/Monkey), tori (酉/Rooster), inu (戌/Dog), i (亥/Boar — notably "boar" rather than "pig"). Since New Year moved to January 1st, the zodiac year transition no longer aligns with the traditional lunisolar boundary.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="tibetan-losar">
      <h2>Tibetan Losar (<span class="chinese-char">ལོ་གསར</span>)</h2>
      <p><strong>Losar</strong> (ལོ་གསར, "new year") is Tibet's most important holiday. The Tibetan calendar is based on the Kālacakra system introduced from India in the 11th century, but it incorporates significant Chinese elements including the twelve-animal zodiac and the five-element system. Losar usually falls near Chinese New Year but can differ by a day, a week, or even a month due to different intercalary month calculations.</p>

      <h3>Distinctive Traditions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Gutor (དགུ་གཏོར)</strong> — On the 29th of the twelfth Tibetan month, families perform elaborate cleansing rituals. A dough ball containing symbolic objects is thrown at a crossroads to cast away the old year's negativity.</li>
        <li><strong>Lama Losar</strong> — The day before New Year is devoted to spiritual practice, with special prayers and offerings at monasteries. Monks perform cham dances (sacred masked dances) to dispel obstacles.</li>
        <li><strong>Changkol (བྱང་ཁོལ)</strong> — A special nine-ingredient soup (guthuk) is prepared, with hidden dough balls containing symbolic items that humorously reveal the finder's character.</li>
        <li><strong>Chemar (ཕྱེ་མར)</strong> — A two-compartmented wooden box filled with tsampa (roasted barley flour) and dried wheat, decorated with coloured butter sculptures. Family members pinch tsampa and toss it in the air three times as an offering.</li>
        <li><strong>Prayer flag renewal</strong> — Old prayer flags on rooftops are replaced with new ones at dawn on Losar, symbolising fresh spiritual energy carried by the wind.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>The Tibetan Zodiac</h3>
      <p>Tibet uses the same twelve animals as China, combined with the five elements to create a sixty-year cycle. However, each element spans two years (male and female), giving a different rhythm to the cycle. The Tibetan year names combine element, gender, and animal: for example, 2026 is a Fire-Male-Horse year (མེ་ཕོ་རྟ).</p>
    </section>

